
Project Glass is a research and development program by Google to develop an augmented reality head-mounted display (HMD).[tpl]cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/2012/04/04/technology/google-project-glass/?source=cnn_bin |publisher=CNN |work=Money |title=Google unveils 'Project Glass' virtual-reality glasses |last=Goldman |first=David |date=4 April 2012 |accessdate=[/tpl] The product (Google Glass Explorer Edition) will be available to United States Google I/O developers for $1500, shipping early in 2013.  CNET - Google Glass Explorer Edition
The intended purpose of Project Glass products would be the hands free displaying of information currently available to most smartphone users,[tpl]cite news |url=http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2402613,00.asp |publisher=PC Magazine |title=Google 'Project Glass' Replaces the Smartphone With Glasses |first=Chloe |last=Albanesius | date=4 April 2012[/tpl] and allowing for interaction with the Internet via natural language voice commands,[tpl]cite news |title=Google's 'Project Glass' Teases Augmented Reality Glasses |url=https://www.pcworld.com/article/253200/googles_project_glass_teases_augmented_reality_glasses.html |publisher=PCWorld |last=Newman |first=Jared | date=4 April 2012[/tpl] in a manner which has been compared to the iPhone feature Siri.[tpl]cite web |url=http://searchengineland.com/meet-project-glass-googles-siri-for-your-eyes-117363 |title=Meet Project Glass: Google's Siri For Your Eyes |last=Sullivan |first=Danny |publisher=Search Engine Land | date= 4 April, 2012 [/tpl] The  operating system software used in the glasses will be Google's Android.[tpl]cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/23/technology/google-glasses-will-be-powered-by-android.html?_r=2 |title=Behind the Google Goggles, Virtual Reality |last=Bilton |first=Nick |publisher=The New York Times | date=23 February 2012[/tpl] 
Project Glass is part of the Google X Lab at the company,[tpl]cite |url=http://techcrunch.com/2012/04/04/google-project-glas/ |title=Google's 'Project Glass' Augmented Reality Glasses Are Real and in Testing |work=Techcrunch |last=Velazco |first=Chris | date=4 April 2012 | accessdate=[/tpl] which has worked on other futuristic technologies, such as a self-driving car. The project was announced on Google+ by Babak Parviz, an electrical engineer who has also worked on putting displays into contact lenses; Steve Lee, a project manager and "geolocation specialist"; and Sebastian Thrun, who developed Udacity as well as working on the self-driving car project.[tpl]cite news |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/business/technology/googles-project-glass-engineers/2012/04/05/gIQACrApxS_story.html |title=Google’s Project Glass engineers: Who are they? |author=Hayley Tsukayama |work=The Washington Post |publisher= |accessdate=5 April 2012|date=5 April 2012[/tpl]

== Prototypes ==

Though head-worn displays for augmented reality are not a new idea, the project has drawn media attention[tpl]cite news |title=A Rose-Colored View May Come Standard |last=Bilton |first=Nick |date=5 April 2012 |publisher=New York Times |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/05/technology/google-offers-look-at-internet-connected-glasses.html |accessdate=[/tpl] primarily due to its backing by Google, as well as the prototype, which is smaller and slimmer than previous designs for head-mounted displays.[tpl]cite web |url=http://www.theverge.com/2012/4/4/2925237/googles-project-glass-augmented-reality-glasses-begin-testing |title=Google's Project Glass augmented reality glasses begin testing |last=Houston |first=Thomas |publisher=The Verge |date=4 April 2012[/tpl] The first Project Glass demo resembles a pair of normal eyeglasses where the lens is replaced by a heads-up display.[tpl]cite news |url=http://www.usatoday.com/tech/news/story/2012-04-04/google-project-glass-augmented-reality/54010466/1 |last=Hatmaker |first=Taylor |publisher=USA Today |title=Google shows off Project Glass | date=4 April 2012 | accessdate=[/tpl] In the future, new designs may allow integration of the display into people's normal eyewear.[tpl]cite news |url=http://www.wired.com/epicenter/2012/04/epicenter-google-glass-ar/ |title=Google Gets Transparent With Glass, Its Augmented Reality Project |last=Levy |first=Steven |publisher=Wired.com |date=4 April 2012[/tpl]
The product began testing in April 2012.[tpl]cite news |title=Google Glasses Sound As Crazy As Smartphones And Tablets Once Did |publisher=Forbes |date=5 April 2012 |accessdate=5 April 2012 |url=http://www.forbes.com/sites/greatspeculations/2012/04/05/google-glasses-sound-as-crazy-as-smartphones-and-tablets-once-did/[/tpl] Sergey Brin wore a prototype set of glasses to an April 5, 2012 Foundation Fighting Blindness event in San Francisco.[tpl]cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/technology/la-na-nn-sergey-brin-project-glass-20120406,0,6029276.story|title=Augmented reality glasses debut on Google co-founder's face|last=Hubbard|first=Amy|date=6 April 2012|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=6 April 2012[/tpl][tpl]cite web|url=http://www.theverge.com/2012/4/6/2929486/googles-project-glass-sergey-brin|title=Google's Sergey Brin takes Project Glass into the wild|last=Bohn|first=Dieter|date=6 April 2012|work=The Verge|accessdate=6 April 2012[/tpl] 
The New York Times reported that the glasses would be available to the public for "around the cost of current smartphones" by the end of 2012,[tpl]cite news |url=http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/02/21/google-to-sell-terminator-style-glasses-by-years-end/ |title=Google to Sell Heads-Up Display Glasses by Year’s End |author=Nick Bilton |date=21 February 2012 |work=The New York Times |publisher= |accessdate=5 April 2012[/tpl] but other reports have stated that the glasses are not expected to be available for purchase soon.[tpl]cite web |url=http://allthingsd.com/20120404/google-unveils-project-glass-wearable-augmented-reality-glasses/ |title=Google Unveils Project Glass: Wearable Augmented-Reality Glasses | accessdate=4 April 2012 |work=All Things Digital |last=Gannes |first=Liz [/tpl][tpl]cite |url=http://thenextweb.com/shareables/2012/04/10/think-googles-project-glass-is-sci-fi-this-developer-hacked-it-together-with-existing-parts/ |title=Think Google Project glass is sci-fi? This developer hacked it together |publisher=The Next Web |last=Knight |first=Jemimah| accessdate=10 April 2012[/tpl][tpl]cite |url=http://www.slashgear.com/diy-project-glass-makes-googles-ar-vision-real-10222231/ |title=DIY Project Glass makes Google’s AR vision real |publisher=SlashGear |last=Davies|first=Chris[/tpl]
Google has patented the design of Project Glass.[tpl]citeweb |url=http://www.bbc.com/news/technology-18091697| title=Google patents augmented reality Project Glass design | accessdate=16 May 2012 | date=16 May 2012 | publisher=BBC[/tpl]
On May 23, Sergey Brin demoed the glasses on The Gavin Newsom Show and let California Lieutenant Governor Gavin Newsom wear the glasses .[tpl]cite news|last=Baldwin|first=Roberto|title=Sergey Brin Finally Lets Someone Else Wear Google Glass ¦ Gadget Lab ¦ Wired.com|url=http://www.wired.com/gadgetlab/2012/05/sergey-brin-finally-lets-someone-else-wear-google-glass/|publisher=Wired|accessdate=31 May 2012|date=29 May 2012[/tpl]
On June 27th, Sergey Brin demoed the glasses at Google I/O using skydivers, abseilers, and Mountain Bikers. http://techcrunch.com/2012/06/27/sergey-brin-demos-google-glass-at-io/

== Reception ==

Despite the generally positive reception for the prototype, there have been numerous parodies and criticisms aimed at the general notion of augmented reality glasses, ranging from the potential for Google to insert advertising (its main source of revenue) to more dystopian outcomes.[tpl]cite |url=http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2402710,00.asp |title=Google's Project Glass Is Really Really Great...For Porn |work=PCMagazine |last=Dvorak |first=John C. |authorlink=John C. Dvorak | date=6 April 2012 [/tpl][tpl]cite |url=http://www.latimes.com/business/technology/la-na-nn-sergey-brin-project-glass-20120406,0,6029276.story |title=Sergey Brin wears Project Glass; Google specs spur fear, punch lines |work=Tech Now |publisher=Los Angeles Times |last=Hubbard |first=Amy [/tpl] Tom Merritt of TWiT famously confused this with SmartGlass.

